 way?<br /><br />Do all the legacy events by default, but then if some user wants a<br />"bind" event (or some other new event) add a model for the uevent<br />interface to actually enable it.<br /><br />Not using kernel versioning (nothing should *ever* look at the kernel<br />version, since that makes things like backports a huge and<br />insurmountable pain), but simply using some specific control channel.<br /><br />&gt; I guess reverting is the right solution here. I wish folks would yell<br />&gt; earlier though...<br /><br />So nobody is actually using the new "bind" event, I take it? It's<br />about a year and a half, and it's in 4.14 which is widely used, so<br />reverting it has a risk too.<br /><br />Which is why I too would hope people would be much more vocal about<br />"that broke my setup".<br /><br />But reverting does sound like the right thing to do if nobody is using<br />it. It sounds like systemd udev does not, and if eudev is actively<br />broken by this then how many other cases might there be?<br /><br />I assume any locally modified udev rules would still be ok with the<br />revert (since presumably any udev rule modification people did was to<br />just ignore the bind/unbind events that no longer would be sent).<br /><br />                Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
